[runAsync][1] takes Runnable as input parameter and returns `CompletableFuture&lt;Void&gt;`, which means it does not return any result.

    CompletableFuture&lt;Void&gt; run = CompletableFuture.runAsync(()-&gt; System.out.println(&quot;hello&quot;));

But [suppyAsync][2] takes Supplier as argument and returns the `CompletableFuture&lt;U&gt;` with result value, which means it does not take any input parameters but it returns result as output.

    CompletableFuture&lt;String&gt; supply = CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -&gt; {
			System.out.println(&quot;Hello&quot;);
			return &quot;result&quot;;
		});

     System.out.println(supply.get());  //result

**Conclusion :** So if you want the result to be returned, then choose `supplyAsync` or if you just want to run an async action, then choose `runAsync`.



  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/concurrent/CompletableFuture.html#runAsync-java.lang.Runnable-
  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/concurrent/CompletableFuture.html#supplyAsync-java.util.function.Supplier-

