### For sorting in Javaâ€¦
You can write your own `Comparator`â€¦

#### `Comparator&lt;LocalDate&gt;`
If you write a custom `Comparator&lt;LocalDate&gt;`, you can simply sort by a *sub-unit* or *part* of the `LocalDate`:  
The `MonthDay`, which only holds information about the day-of-month and the month-of-year and it is already implementing `Comparable&lt;MonthDay&gt;` exactly as desired.

#### Code example
```Java
public static void main(String[] args) {
	// create the list of Strings to be sorted
	List&lt;String&gt; birthdayStrings = List.of(
				&quot;2004-03-05&quot;,
				&quot;2001-03-03&quot;,
				&quot;2003-12-08&quot;,
				&quot;2015-10-08&quot;,
				&quot;1999-09-24&quot;,
				&quot;1999-07-16&quot;,
				&quot;2005-01-28&quot;
			);
	// map this list to a sortable one by parsing the Strings to LocalDates
	List&lt;LocalDate&gt; birthdays = birthdayStrings.stream()
											   .map(LocalDate::parse)
											   .collect(Collectors.toList());
	// print the list once
	birthdays.forEach(System.out::println);
	// print some separator in order to visually separate the unsorted from the sorted result
	System.out.println(&quot;â€”&quot;.repeat(12));
	// define a comparator for LocalDates that sorts by month-of-year first, then by day-of-month
	Comparator&lt;LocalDate&gt; monthDayComp = new Comparator&lt;LocalDate&gt;() {
		@Override
		public int compare(LocalDate o1, LocalDate o2) {
			// simply sort by (already comparable) part of the LocalDate: MonthDay
			return MonthDay.from(o1).compareTo(MonthDay.from(o2));
		}
	};
	// sort the list using the comparator
	birthdays.sort(monthDayComp);
	// print the sorted list
	birthdays.forEach(System.out::println);
}
```

#### Output
```none
2004-03-05
2001-03-03
2003-12-08
2015-10-08
1999-09-24
1999-07-16
2005-01-28
â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”
2005-01-28
2001-03-03
2004-03-05
1999-07-16
1999-09-24
2015-10-08
2003-12-08
```

